        -:    1:// First-fit implementation of malloc.
        -:    2:
        -:    3:// Definitions:
        -:    4://
        -:    5://   Small blocks: b locks that are managed with first fit.
        -:    6://
        -:    7://   Large blocks: are memory-mapped rather than managed with first fit.
        -:    8://    "large" maens >= `mmap_lower_bound`, which is tentatively, `1<<18`.
        -:    9://
        -:   10://   Word: 8 bytes.
        -:   11://
        -:   12://   Page: 4096 bytes (we have `page_size == 4096`).
        -:   13://
        -:   14://   Boundary tag: [the idea is due to Knuth TAOCP vol 1].  The malloc functions
        -:   15://    return a pointer to the user.  Just before that pointer is a word
        -:   16://    containing a header, called the boundary tag. The boundary tag is 1 word containing
        -:   17://      ```
        -:   18://      struct boundary_tag {
        -:   19://          size_t is_memaligned:1;
        -:   20://          size_t size:63;
        -:   21://      }}
        -:   22://      ```
        -:   23://
        -:   24://    The meaning is this:
        -:   25://
        -:   26://      If `is_memaligned` is `false` then `size` is the number of bytes in the
        -:   27://        block.  if `size` is >= `mmap_lower_bound` then the block is mmapped.
        -:   28://        The size must be a multiple of `page_size`.
        -:   29://
        -:   30://      If `is_memaligned` is `true` then we this block is the result of a call
        -:   31://        to `posix_memalign` or `aligned_alloc` or `memalign`.  To allocate a
        -:   32://        block of size `s` aligned to `a` (which must be a power of two) we
        -:   33://        need to allocate extra bytes and then waste part of the allocation.
        -:   34://        The idea is that if we allocate `s + a - 1` bytes, then somewhere in
        -:   35://        the resulting block there is a block of size `s` that is aligned to
        -:   36://        `a`.  For a memaligned block we need a 2-word header: The first is
        -:   37://        a pointer to the actual beginning of the block, and the second is our
        -:   38://        header with `is_memaligned==true`.  The `size` is the size of the
        -:   39://        originally allocated block.  (And if `size >= mmap_lower_bound` then
        -:   40://        the originally allocated block is allocated via mmap and the size is a
        -:   41://        multiple of `page_size`.)
        -:   42://
        -:   43://        When allocating a memaligned block, one could imagine peeling off the
        -:   44://        unused memory at the beginning of the allocation and making it
        -:   45://        available for different allocation.  Doing so could be problematic,
        -:   46://        however, sine the resulting block would be in the wrong place for
        -:   47://        first fit.  You could end up with a very small block at a very high
        -:   48://        address, which would violate the invariant proved in Robson77 (Section
        -:   49://        3) that small blocks appear only at low addresses. For memaligned
        -:   50://        blocks, the extra block wouldn't even be in the right part of the
        -:   51://        address space.  So instead, we simply treat the unused memory as part
        -:   52://        of the allocation.
        -:   53://
        -:   54://        We also special-case alignment==8, since that adds no alignment
        -:   55://        constraints: it just directly calls malloc, which always returns
        -:   56://        8-byte aligned values.
